      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your Sept. 8 Weekend section article about stickball reminded me of the girls' equivalent activity back in the Bronx at midcentury. We bounced our spaldeens and then ''turned over,'' too.</p>
        <p>Turning over meant lifting a leg and arcing a knee around a bouncing ball while chanting a particular rhyme. ''A, my name is Alice'' was one such ditty. It was an alphabetical run requiring bouncers to turn over on every word beginning with the designated letter.</p>
        <p>During recess in the Public School 28 schoolyard, some girls were capable of ''turning over'' 10 consecutive times. Does anyone bounce balls anymore?</p>
        <p>ROBERTA TEMES  Brooklyn, Sept. 8, 2000</p>
      </block>
